    "### 1.1 Background & Motivation\n",
    " \n",
    "Climate change mitigation requires more than blanket awareness campaigns — it demands **targeted interventions** that address the specific behaviours driving carbon emissions in different population segments. A household that commutes daily by private petrol car faces entirely different reduction opportunities than one whose footprint is dominated by air travel and high consumption of new clothing.\n",
    " \n",
    "This project uses an individual-level carbon-emission survey dataset (10,000 respondents) that captures lifestyle dimensions such as diet, transport mode, energy source, waste habits, and consumption patterns alongside each person's estimated annual carbon emission (kg CO₂). By applying unsupervised clustering to these behavioural features, we aim to **discover distinct lifestyle-emission profiles** — groups of people who share similar carbon-relevant habits — and translate those profiles into actionable, segment-specific sustainability recommendations.\n",
    " \n",
    "The driving question guiding this capstone is:\n",
    " \n",
    "> *How can clustering help us uncover hidden patterns in individual carbon-emission data that lead to more sustainable and equitable decisions?*"
   ]
  },
