    "#### Cluster Interpretation Strategy\n",
    " \n",
    "Given the mixed-type, high-dimensional nature of this data, interpretation will follow five steps:\n",
    " \n",
    "1. **Centroid profiling** — For each K-Means cluster, extract centroid values and identify the 3–5 features where each cluster deviates most from the population mean. These are the defining behaviours of that segment.\n",
    " \n",
    "2. **Emission validation** — Overlay `CarbonEmission` (excluded from clustering) onto clusters. If behaviourally distinct clusters also show distinct emission levels, the segmentation is both coherent and emission-relevant.\n",
    " \n",
    "3. **Categorical mode analysis** — Compute the mode of nominal features (diet, transport, heating source) within each cluster to build clear behavioural narratives (e.g., \"80% use private transport, 70% are omnivores\").\n",
    " \n",
    "4. **Visual communication** — Radar charts for cluster profiles, box plots for emission distributions per cluster, heatmaps for feature means across all clusters.\n",
    " \n",
    "5. **Naming and narrative** — Assign each cluster an intuitive label (e.g., \"Green Commuters,\" \"High-Consumption Drivers\") and write a one-paragraph persona that non-technical stakeholders can understand and act on.\n",
    " \n",
    "**Key interpretation challenges to watch for:**\n",
    "- Clusters driven by one-hot encoding artifacts rather than meaningful behaviours → validate with original categorical distributions\n",
    "- PCA-transformed features are hard to interpret → map back to original features via component loadings\n",
    "- DBSCAN outlier cluster may be too small for full profiling → report count and flag for manual review"
   ]
