    "| **Punitive targeting** | Policymakers may use profiles to impose penalties (taxes, fines) without providing alternatives — disproportionately harming low-income groups. | Impact brief explicitly recommends support-first interventions and cautions against punitive use. |\n",
    "| **Survey representation bias** | If the survey over-represents urban or higher-income populations, clusters may miss marginalised communities entirely. | Acknowledge sample limitations; recommend validation against local demographics before designing interventions. |\n",
    "| **Within-cluster diversity flattened** | Every member gets the same label, but reasons for behaviour (income, disability, rural isolation) vary enormously. | Report within-cluster variance; note that clusters are starting points, not individual prescriptions. |\n",
    "| **Privacy and profiling** | Cluster profiles linked to geographic identifiers could enable discriminatory profiling. | Recommend profiles remain aggregate-level; no individual or micro-geographic linking without ethical review. |\n",
    " \n",
    "**How this project promotes justice:**\n",
    " \n",
    "- **Distributive justice** — Distinguishes \"choice-based\" from \"constraint-based\" high emitters so resources reach those who lack alternatives.\n",
    "- **Procedural justice** — Impact brief is written accessibly for community organisations, ensuring affected populations can participate in interpreting results.\n",
    "- **Recognition justice** — The \"green exemplar\" cluster celebrates existing sustainable behaviours rather than framing climate action only as a deficit.\n",
